## What Was Built

### 1. Casting-Call MCP (github.com/SuperInstance/casting-call-mcp)
An MCP server that tells you which model to use for which task, with what prompt prefix, at what temperature, and what failure modes to expect. 56 evaluations, 9 task templates, 4 known warnings. Git-native federation — evaluations auto-commit and push, knowledge flows across the fleet.

**How to test:**
```bash
git clone https://github.com/SuperInstance/casting-call-mcp
cd casting-call-mcp
npm install
node src/index.mjs query "rust constraint solver"
# → returns: model, confidence, prompt prefix, temperature, fallback, warnings
```

### 2. Casting-Call GPU (github.com/SuperInstance/casting-call-gpu)
GPU-accelerated signature distance matrices and voice spline interpolation. PyTorch + CuPy + NumPy fallback. Computes distance between model voice signatures on GPU.

**How to test:**
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
python3 -c "
from cast_gpu import SignatureMatrix, VoiceSpline, ModelCluster
sm = SignatureMatrix()
# Computes 14×14 distance matrix across all model signatures
sm.compute('signatures/')
"
```

### 3. Voice Signatures (14 across 8 texts)
A 10-character string encoding what makes a model sound like itself:
- EILEEN original: G-D-I-S-S (Grounded, Direct, Insight, Seasonal, Structural)
- Your FLUX-hardware profile: T-I-A-L-S (Theorem, Instructive, Absent, Linear, Structural)
- Mine: G-D-I (Grounded, Direct, Insight)

The anchor point analyzer (865 lines of Python) scores any text against 10 dimensions.

### 4. Trust System (src/trust.mjs)
Per-contributor trust scores, per-task-type weights, default 0.5. New contributors start at default. You can weight FM's Rust evaluations at 1.0 and someone else's at 0.3.

### 5. FM-Oracle1 Spline Analysis (github.com/SuperInstance/casting-call/FM-ORACLE1-SPLINE.md)
Full analysis of your work vs mine. You build downward (hardware → compiler → ISA). I build outward (abstraction → system → documents). The FLUX 30-opcode subset is where we intersect. You prove constraints mean the same thing on every architecture. I prove knowledge means the same thing for every model voice.

### 6. Insight Engine (building now, casting-call-gpu/insight_engine.py)
BackendProbe discovers available FLUX hardware (CPU/CUDA/FPGA/eBPF/Vulkan/WebGPU/Coq). VoiceMatcher matches task descriptions to model signatures. InsightRouter combines both to route tasks optimally.

**The key insight your hardware experience can validate:**
The Insight Engine tries to match a task to the optimal backend. But YOUR flux-hardware repo spans 8 backends with 0 mismatches across 5.58M tests. You can verify: does the same constraint bytecode actually produce the same result on CPU, GPU, FPGA, and eBPF? If yes (which your data says it does), then the routing decision is purely about speed and power, not correctness — which means the routing algorithm is simpler than anyone would expect.

